{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519164"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:09:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:09:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12986"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12986"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.16,0.45,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5424"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12986"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89153"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"768"},{"type":"tags","id":"1309"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6352"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33237"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43376"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a painful right ankle. He was playing basketball and accidentally rolled his ankle an hour ago, resulting in a sudden onset of severe pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 126/78 mmHg, pulse 90/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 18/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 100% on room air. He is unable to weight bear on the right foot and it looks deformed, but there are no signs of injury to the skin. On palpation, there is tenderness over the lateral malleolus and midfoot. His neurovascular status is unremarkable. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Closed reduction","Casting and immobilisation","Open reduction and internal fixation","Moonboot","External fixation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a Weber type B fracture of the fibula with widened medial clear space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClosed reduction \u003C/strong\u003Eis the correct first-line management in this scenario. The management of ankle fractures depends on whether the injury is open or closed. In this case, there are no skin breaks on examination (closed) and the X-ray shows displacement of the fracture. In order to minimise the risk of neurovascular injury and injury to the soft tissues from shearing forces, closed manual reduction of the fracture is indicated as first-line management in order to realign the fracture. This is done with sedation / analgesia administered before manual reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen reduction and internal fixation (ORIF) \u003C/strong\u003Eis the definitive management option for this patient\u0027s fracture, with the displaced fracture and talar shift (widened medial clear space). However, surgery is only done after initial management of closed reduction and stabilisation of the fracture has occurred, and this option is not the first-line management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECasting and immobilisation\u003C/strong\u003E are usually done after closed reduction of an undisplaced fracture. Patients are advised to non weight bear for four weeks before converting to a removable walking cast to facilitate weight bearing and mobility. However, the patient has a displaced Weber B fracture which requires initial closed reduction with appropriate analgesia, followed by surgical management (ORIF).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMoonboot\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this option should only be considered in undisplaced fractures, which is usually used for 6-8 weeks until bony healing has occurred. As this patient has a displaced fracture, a moonboot would not aid in fracture healing but it can be used to assist in walking and minimising pain symptoms. Furthermore, the fracture is displaced and closed reduction should be the initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal fixation \u003C/strong\u003Eis one of the techniques used mainly for open ankle fractures or fractures with significant soft tissue swelling. However, it is usually used as a temporary measure to stabilise the fracture and allow soft tissue healing before open reduction and internal fixation can be undertaken. The patient does not require open reduction and internal fixation, and a non-invasive approach would be preferential.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Weber classification of ankle fractures can be remembered as: Type A (below the syndesmosis), Type B (at level of the syndesmosis) and Type C (above the syndesmosis)","Initial management of a closed Weber B fracture is closed reduction, followed by referral to orthopaedics for open reduction and internal fixation."],"references":["Goost H, Wimmer MD, Barg A, Kabir K, Valderrabano V, Burger C. Fractures of the ankle joint: investigation and treatment options. Deutsches \u00c4rzteblatt International. 2014 May;111(21):377. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24939377/","Wire J, Hermena S, Slane VH. Ankle fractures. In: Statpearls [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542324/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89153"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12986"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20282"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20282"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GhePmaYXuiLevcj6L1KlDBSqtF4WuR.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GhePmaYXuiLevcj6L1KlDBSqtF4WuR.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":563,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89153"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-21T18:20:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-21T18:20:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5424"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{